For toadstool cafe I was able to give them my phone number to put in a reservation then they text you when your reservation is ready. Then I was able to play games and come back when ready. About 15 minutes after I gave them my number they messaged me they were ready for the cafe. I did have to come back a different day to meet Mario since line was quick when he comes and they don’t let anybody just get in line. But now with if officially being open things have changed so I assume a much longer wait but following the universal hollywood fans Facebook group will help you get an idea as well. text:
Experience Bayonetta's origins as a young witch named Cereza as she partners up with the demon Cheshire. You'll strategically control both characters at once as you explore a dangerous forest.

Bayonetta Origins: Cereza and the Lost Demon arrives 3/17, pre-orders are available now.

text:

'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None, 'replies': [{'comment_id': '857329292218597', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/857329292218597', 'commenter_id': '100004560468941', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Ilko Skevüld', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Juls Montejo The English translation for Mother 3 has been available since 2008, and the fact that it's still available and was even updated recently points to Nintendo not having any interest in releasing it in the west officially. If they did, they'd likely censor it anyway, so I'm perfectly happy with what we have.", 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '1153207102231548', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/1153207102231548', 'commenter_id': '100001398605162', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Evan J Field', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Ilko Skevüld For all intents and purposes. Nintendo has never taken down fan translations before. They've also never gone back and translated Japan exclusive games before, with the only exception being Fire Emblem 1", 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '489495189973759', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/489495189973759', 'commenter_id': '100004560468941', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Ilko Skevüld', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Evan J Field Maybe people got a glimmer of hope with the release of EarthBound Beginnings, at least if they were unaware that they completed the official translation of that game 25 years prior to its eventual release. Nintendo were basically just sitting on free money with it, and they didn't even retroactively change anything for consistency with the sequel.", 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '849370926271133', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/849370926271133', 'commenter_id': '100001398605162', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Evan J Field', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': 'Ilko Skevüld Yup. Nintendo typically doesn't go around altering their old roms. If there's some licensing issue preventing re-release, Nintendo would rather let the game sit on a shelf than make changes to remove the offending issue.

For example, re-releasing Tetris Attack would likely be as simple as changing the name to something like "Yoshi's Puzzle League" and removing all instances of the word "Tetris," but simply giving us Panel de Pon and leaving it in Japanese requires less manpower and costs a lot less to do, so that's what we get', 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '897246861636219', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/897246861636219', 'commenter_id': '100004560468941', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Ilko Skevüld', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Evan J Field To be fair, I recall that when StarTropics was released on Wii Virtual Console, they went back in the ROM and changed the yo-yos to be called stars... for some reason. I remember this specifically because at the time, the EB fan community was fully expectant that if Nintendo did put EB on VC, they'd have gone in and scrubbed out various pop culture references, such as mentioning The Beatles by name in Onett. I remember when I bought the game on Wii U, as soon as I could, I went to that door in Onett to see if that joke was still in there, and being excited when it was.", 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '570770768220720', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/570770768220720', 'commenter_id': '100001398605162', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Evan J Field', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': 'Ilko Skevüld True, there are some exceptions here and there. The most notable example I can think of is going back and re-translating the opening crawl of Zelda 1 (but not the rest of the game) for the Collection on GameCube, which is also the version used in every subsequent re-release of the game', 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}, {'comment_id': '693487112430342', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/693487112430342', 'commenter_id': '100004560468941', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Ilko Skevüld', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': "Evan J Field Sure, and they changed a small bit of text in Link's Awakening as well, which I think was curiously restored in the Game & Watch release. But that's Zelda, one of their biggest franchises. If Nintendo really did have as many problems with EB as the fans were having to assume in the late 2000s, they probably wouldn't have deemed it worthwhile to change. I'm glad they've put the first two out at all, and both largely unchanged. A few more of my friends have played those games since, and though I don't understand it personally, I suppose I do hope M3 ends up on the platform, just so more people can experience that wonderful, beautiful game.", 'comment_time': datetime.datetime(2022, 12, 29, 0, 0), 'comment_image': None, 'comment_reactors': [], 'comment_reactions': None, 'comment_reaction_count': None}]}, {'comment_id': '1381815629290477', 'comment_url': 'https://facebook.com/1381815629290477', 'commenter_id': '100002340320951', 'commenter_url': None, 'commenter_name': 'Hazel Nutz Malinao', 'commenter_meta': None, 'comment_text': 'Mother 3 Nintendo?
